  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Externalities and Social Optimum</h2>

    <div class="key-terms">
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Externality</div><div class="definition">A cost or benefit imposed on a third party not involved in the transaction. External effects are not reflected in the market price.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Marginal Private Cost (MPC)</div><div class="definition">The cost of producing one more unit borne by the producer. Shown as the supply curve in a private market.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Marginal Private Benefit (MPB)</div><div class="definition">The benefit of consuming one more unit received by the consumer. Shown as the demand curve in a private market.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Marginal Social Cost (MSC)</div><div class="definition">MPC + Marginal External Cost (MEC). The full cost to society of producing one more unit.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Marginal Social Benefit (MSB)</div><div class="definition">MPB + Marginal External Benefit (MEB). The full benefit to society of consuming one more unit.</div></div>
      <div class="key-term-card"><div class="term">Social optimum</div><div class="definition">The allocatively efficient output where MSB = MSC. Social surplus is maximised.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">The Four Types of Externality</h2>

    <h3>Negative Externality of Production</h3>
    <p>A producer imposes external costs on third parties (e.g., a factory polluting a river). MSC > MPC. The market overproduces relative to the social optimum (Q<sub>market</sub> > Q<sub>opt</sub>). There is a welfare loss (deadweight loss) — the triangle between MSC and MPB (=MSB) for units between Q<sub>opt</sub> and Q<sub>market</sub>.</p>
    <p><strong>Examples:</strong> industrial pollution, carbon emissions, noise from airports.</p>

    <h3>Negative Externality of Consumption (Demerit Goods)</h3>
    <p>A consumer imposes external costs on others (e.g., smokers affecting passive smokers). MSB < MPB. Market overconsumes relative to social optimum.</p>
    <p><strong>Examples:</strong> cigarettes, alcohol, junk food.</p>

    <h3>Positive Externality of Production</h3>
    <p>A producer creates external benefits for third parties (e.g., a beekeeper's bees pollinating nearby crops). MSC > MPC is reversed: MSC < MPC. Market underproduces relative to social optimum.</p>
    <p><strong>Examples:</strong> technology research and development, reforestation.</p>

    <h3>Positive Externality of Consumption (Merit Goods)</h3>
    <p>A consumer creates external benefits for others by consuming a good (e.g., vaccination reduces disease spread). MSB > MPB. Market underconsumes relative to social optimum.</p>
    <p><strong>Examples:</strong> education, healthcare, vaccines.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Common Pool Resources</h2>
    <p><strong>Common pool resources</strong> (also called common access resources) are goods that are:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Rivalrous</strong> — one person's use reduces availability to others</li>
      <li><strong>Non-excludable</strong> — it is difficult or impossible to prevent people from using them</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Examples: ocean fisheries, groundwater, forests, atmospheric capacity to absorb CO₂.</p>

    <h3>Tragedy of the Commons</h3>
    <p>Because no one owns common pool resources, individuals have an incentive to exploit them before others do — each individual acting in self-interest leads to overuse and depletion of the resource. This is the <strong>tragedy of the commons</strong> (Hardin, 1968). It is a form of market failure — the private market overuses the resource relative to the socially sustainable level.</p>
    <p>This creates <strong>negative externalities</strong> (unsustainable production imposing costs on future generations and others).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Government Responses</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Policy</th><th>How it works</th><th>Target</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Indirect (Pigouvian) tax</strong></td><td>Tax on negative externalities to internalise the external cost; raises the producer's MPC to equal MSC</td><td>Negative externalities of production/consumption</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Carbon tax</strong></td><td>A specific Pigouvian tax on carbon emissions; raises price of fossil fuels to reduce CO₂ output</td><td>Negative externality of production (climate)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Subsidy</strong></td><td>Payment to producers or consumers to shift supply/demand right, increasing output toward social optimum</td><td>Positive externalities</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Legislation and regulation</strong></td><td>Direct limits on output, emissions, or behaviour (e.g., pollution limits, bans on harmful activities)</td><td>Both negative externalities and common pool resources</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Tradable permits</strong></td><td>Government sets a cap on total emissions; firms are allocated permits; they can trade. Creates a market price for pollution.</td><td>Negative externalities of production</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Education and awareness</strong></td><td>Campaigns to change consumer behaviour (e.g., anti-smoking campaigns)</td><td>Negative externalities of consumption (demerit goods)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Government provision</strong></td><td>Direct provision of merit goods (e.g., free healthcare, public education)</td><td>Positive externalities of consumption</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Collective self-governance</strong></td><td>Communities manage shared resources together (e.g., fishing quotas set by local fishermen)</td><td>Common pool resources</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>International agreements</strong></td><td>Treaties to manage global commons (e.g., Paris Agreement on climate, fishing treaties)</td><td>Global common pool resources</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout hl-only">
      <div class="callout-title">HL only — Calculating welfare loss</div>
      <p>Welfare loss (deadweight loss) is the area of the triangle between the social optimum output and the market output, bounded by the MSC and MSB curves.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:0.5rem;">For a negative externality of production: welfare loss = ½ × (Q<sub>market</sub> − Q<sub>opt</sub>) × (MSC − MSB) at Q<sub>market</sub></p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Externality: cost/benefit on a third party not in the transaction</li>
      <li>Negative externality → overproduction/consumption; positive → underproduction/consumption</li>
      <li>MSC = MPC + MEC; MSB = MPB + MEB</li>
      <li>Social optimum: MSB = MSC</li>
      <li>Common pool resources: rivalrous + non-excludable → tragedy of the commons</li>
      <li>Key policies: Pigouvian tax, carbon tax, tradable permits, regulation, subsidies</li>
      <li>International cooperation needed for global externalities</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

