  <h2>Worked Example — Negative Externality of Production <span class="hl-badge">HL</span></h2>
  <p>A coal-fired power plant operates in a competitive market. The market price is $50 and market output is 1,000 MWh. The social optimum output is 700 MWh at a price of $70 (where MSB = MSC). The external cost per unit is $30.</p>

  <h3>Welfare loss triangle</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    Welfare loss = ½ × base × height<br>
    Base = Q<sub>market</sub> − Q<sub>opt</sub> = 1,000 − 700 = 300<br>
    Height = MEC at Q<sub>market</sub> = $30<br>
    Welfare loss = ½ × 300 × $30 = <strong>$4,500</strong>
  </div>

  <h3>Corrective Pigouvian tax</h3>
  <div class="answer-content" style="display:block;">
    To internalise the externality, the tax should equal the MEC = <strong>$30 per MWh</strong>.<br>
    This raises MPC to equal MSC, shifting the supply curve left to the social optimum output of 700 MWh.
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-8">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Practice questions are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions</div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Explain, using a diagram, why a free market leads to overproduction when there is a negative externality of production.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          In a free market with a negative externality of production, the supply curve reflects only MPC — producers do not account for the external cost imposed on third parties. The market equilibrium is where MPB = MPC. However, the social optimum is where MSB = MSC. Since MSC > MPC, the social optimum output is lower than the market output (Q<sub>opt</sub> &lt; Q<sub>market</sub>). The market overproduces, creating a welfare loss (deadweight loss) — the triangular area between MSC and MSB for the overproduced units.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Explain the concept of "tragedy of the commons" using ocean fisheries as an example.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Ocean fisheries are a common pool resource — they are rivalrous (catching fish reduces availability for others) but non-excludable (it is difficult to stop fishers from accessing the ocean). Each fishing boat has an incentive to catch as many fish as possible before others do. Individually rational behaviour leads to collective overexploitation: fish stocks are depleted to the point of collapse, harming all future users. No individual has an incentive to conserve because the benefits of restraint are shared while the costs are private.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. Evaluate the effectiveness of a carbon tax as a policy to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          <strong>Strengths:</strong> A carbon tax internalises the negative externality by raising the price of carbon-intensive goods, incentivising producers and consumers to reduce emissions. It uses the price mechanism and generates government revenue that can fund green investment or compensate affected households. It is relatively easy to implement through existing tax systems.<br><br>
          <strong>Limitations:</strong> Setting the correct tax rate is difficult — measuring the true social cost of carbon is complex and contested. If set too low, the tax fails to reduce emissions to the social optimum. Carbon taxes are regressive (fall disproportionately on lower-income households who spend more of their income on energy). Without international coordination, carbon taxes may cause "carbon leakage" — firms relocate to countries with no carbon price, shifting emissions rather than reducing them.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

